All those frequent baptisms for which Jesus derided the then accepted tradition of God's will were to its devotees- the outward recognition of their belief that human defilement must be washed away ere the simplest blessing could be re- ceived, the simplest action performed in the presence of God. The Pharisees did not believe that washings were of avail except as a fulfilment of the divine command.
